node.text:
I recently started following this bomb.com self help coach on my personal Instagram account. @therealjoirizarry 

Her daily convos/advice/ viewpoints are spot on in this stage of growth and healing. 

This particular post resonates with me as I started setting hella boundaries. Now I can identify that empty feeling, the loss that she speaks of. Maybe you can relate?

node.text: Our weekly LIVE with @daria_tsvenger is back 🤗🌟 Follow @daria_tsvenger for more tips on making friends 👋

node.title: HOW TO MAKE FRIENDS, EVEN IF YOU’RE AN INTROVERT 🌟

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by A Safe Place Inside Your Head on September 07, 2021 tagging @tanner_hamilton22. May be a meme of one or more people and text that says 'When I accidentally tell someone too much about how I'm feeling I was lying by the way I'm fine'.

node.text:
I used to barely talk about how I’m feeling because I got left feeling like this so much. I’ve gotten better about opening up but only to the right people…if you are in my circle just know I appreciate you listening to me and I am sure you know I would do the same for you. I hope everyone has a beautiful Tuesday. - @tanner_hamilton22 
.
.
.
.
.
.
#suicideawarenessmonth #asafeplaceinsideyourhead #keepgoing #trytoopenup #youallarebeautiful #howcanwehelp #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmatters

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by A Safe Place Inside Your Head in Austin, Texas. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'My brain recording my good memories My brain recording my cringe memories'.

node.text:
Why is that we vividly remember every cringe worthy memory that we have made in our lifetime?

And why do we remember them every time we try to go to sleep at night? 

Why can I barely remember something good that happened just yesterday? 

Just, why? - @therealjoirizarry 
.
.
.
.
.
#somanyunansweredquestions #overthinking #iamanoverthinker #toomanyrandomthoughts #racingthoughts😣 #mentalhealthadvocate💚 #mentalhealthmemes🖤 #suicideawarenessmonth #safeplaceinsideyourhead

You're not entitled to someone's down time. True friends understand that you can't pour from an empty cup'.

node.text:
That’s me, I’m the friend. 

I’m not gonna lie. When I need a break from reality, I turn to media and leave out the social part. Sometimes I wanna be alone and just meme hunt and laugh or find content that helps me get my head back on straight. It doesn’t mean I want to comment or engage, i just wanna be somewhere in the background. 

So give your friends like me one small break. Give them time and space to unwind. 

Now back to meme hunting …… 😆 @therealjoirizarry

I tell people I have social anxiety…some people tell me I need to be more social and it will go away. I’m not sure that’s how that works 🤔. It’s getting better though, but I’ll move at my own speed. Just a heads up though if someone talks to you about their anxiety, just listen and meet them where they are at. Advice like the one in the meme isn’t optimal and can cause feelings of invalidation. I personally prefer “I’m here for you, I understand and see why you feel that way” better. Anyone else feel this way? - @tanner_hamilton22

suicide prevention month is a great way to bring awareness to a topic that is often avoided in our daily lives. but the reality is, suicide exists every month whether we like it or not. here are some of the key signs to look out for if someone in your life is contemplating suicide.
• irritability 
• mood swings
• giving away belongings
• suddenly happy 
• talks about death/dying (this includes saying ‘kms’)
• no longer engaging in activities they normally liked
• decreased performance in school

now we know the warning signs. what happens next? tomorrow i’ll be posting ways you can help.

node.text:
TW: Suicide 

Therapy has saved my life. A few years ago I had to check myself into a mental health hospital because I was actively suicidal and got caught in the middle of an attempt. I got scooped up by an ambulance and taken to JPS in Fort Worth before being taken to Mesa Springs. I was a mess, just recently divorced, heavy drug problems, and literally everything that could go wrong that was self inflicted was going wrong. I was in the worst spot I’ve ever been in, and was hurting more than I could even imagine. When I first got to Mesa Springs I didn’t buy into all the things that were going on, would skip classes, or basically anything to do the bare minimum. The turning point for my stay and my life to get to the point where I was at now was the question “is this how you want your daughter to remember you” and those words rang so loudly in my head…so basically after that conversation with the person I shared a room with I turned it around. I bought into the healing process and allowed for the methods I was being taught to better myself, and by doing that I got better. I worked on who I was and dealt with the demons that were causing me so much despair…my mental health was now manageable by the time I left that place. It wasn’t always fun and the self work the therapist there put me through helped. I’m not ashamed that I had to go to the hospital, I needed that. I’m telling my story during #suicideawarenessmonth so more people know they aren’t alone in the process and that it does get better in time. Not everyone’s story will look like this but we want to help in any way we can to ensure no person feels alone in their journey. I am a survivor. - @tanner_hamilton22
